        <div class="span-15" id="content">
          <h3 class="loud">Could you explain the main purpose of this site?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              As earlier mentioned, the JNoM project is a personal website designed and developed as partial requirement for completion of my programming class in freshman year, college. To that effect, it also serves as a personal portfolio with a variety of music, literature and art to be showcased personally by yours truly.
          </p>
          
          <h3 class="loud">Did you design/develop this website yourself?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              Yes, indeed I did. Members of a basic Website Design and Development Team would normally include: the project manager, the webmaster, the application developer, the systems administrator, and the graphic artist. For this project, however, a single individual (that being myself, of course) has covered all these roles for the purpose of accomplishing this given website project. 
          </p>

          <h3 class="loud">How long did it take you to finish the site?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              The creation of this site can be divided into two stages: alpha and beta testing. Alpha comprised of first familiarizing with the instruments to be used in development. Learning the different languages (HTML5, CSS, Ruby) and tools (Rails, Mockflow) used for development took well over three weeks through testing, experimenting, and exploring. Afterwards, Beta would comprise of development of the actual site, which originally went through several redesigns before arriving at the conclusion with this minimalist personal site: the JNoM Project. Overall web structure and basic design elements took about two days to accomplish (meaning finishing about 90% of the site in that duration). Finishing touches, tweaks, and misc. content input followed after in a span of five more days. This means the actual site you see now took around one week to reach completion.
          </p>
        
          <h3 class="loud">What tools/languages did you use to accomplish this project?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              The development of this website predominantly incorporates the use of HTML5, Blueprint CSS, and a Ruby on Rails framework. Graphic design and prototyping required the use of several editor software, including Adobe Photoshop CS 5.5, ColorSchemer Studio, and MockFlow. Testing was conducted in Google Chrome v11.0.696.65 and Mozilla Firefox v6.0. Browser plug-ins used to aid in this project include FireBug and the WebDev Toolbar. Possible use of embedded content, JavaScript, and Php are also be noted where necessary.
          </p>
  
          <h3 class="loud">What would be the best settings to view this site with?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              For optimum visual display, it would be safest to use the latest versions of either Google Chrome of Mozilla Firefox to ensure HTML5 support. CSS implementation, however, has been arranged to allow design resets that will cope with lesser versions of other browsers as not to compromise site accessibility. Beta stage of the website will not require plug-ins for flash content, but this may change in the future. A screen resolution of 1280 x 800 was used for testing the website. Colours may vary from one monitor unit to another, but colour palette standards were used for this web project.
          </p>
          
          <h3 class="loud">How would you describe the accessibility of this website?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              As mentioned above, for optimum website navigation, the use of the latest versions of popular browsers would be recommended to ensure support for the language the site is written and to cater to any possible future modifications. Bandwidth load should be reduced significantly by the clean, simplistic structure of this webapp. Deployment has been placed under the moderation of the EngineYard web hosting environment, initially under free/trial subscription for the live testing phase of the Rails app. It will be expected that there will be relatively low-traffic in the earlier stages of deployment, but the site will definitely be fully accessible for academic purposes.
          </p>
          
          <h3 class="loud">How did you work with the overall design/colorscheme of the site?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              No automatic code generating software was allowed in the creation of this website, so the entire design is arranged and hardcoded using Blueprint CSS, a webdesign framework. This allowed for using divs and such to arrange the various content in the different pages of this web development project. The color palette used in the design was extracted from the banner image using ColorSchemer Pro to match the entire theme of the site.
          </p>
          
          <h3 class="loud">How long have you been working in programming and web development?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              Since both in the question were part of my highschool curriculum, I would say I started learning since my first year in secondary school.
              Having been taught to write HTML in freshman year, and trained to manage a webdevelopment project by senior year, both helped me advance
              in this project a bit faster than I would have been able to otherwise. Also, having been employed as a graphic artist since 2011, I've gained some actual work experience in webdesign as well after being hired to assist the company's Creative Director with a client's website development commission. That would mean I have been playing around with these concepts for around four to five years now, including this project in freshman college.
          </p>
          
          <h3 class="loud">Will you be willing to take commissions for webdevelopment in the future?</h3>
          <p align="justify">
              Of course! As a working student, I take every opportunity I can to earn, especially if it means I will be allowed to help another person in the process. Although I am currently employed as a graphic artist, I also freelance in taking up commissions for any potential client. I will take anything that is within my ability, not just web development, including layout and design and avp production.
          </p>
          
